post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_20797979_20798081_0": {"length": 6, "quality": 0.5454545454545454, "section_id": 551}}, "n3337": {"so_20797979_20798081_0": {"length": 7, "quality": 0.6363636363636364, "section_id": 542}}, "n4659": {"so_20797979_20798081_0": {"length": 6, "quality": 0.5454545454545454, "section_id": 572}}}, "20798125": {"Id": "20798125", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>Without knowing what you really want to do ...</p>\n<p>If you want to declare a string:</p>\n<pre><code>char * x = \"Game\";\nstring xs = \"Game\"; // C++\n</code></pre>\n<p>If you want to declare a char:</p>\n<pre><code>char y = 'G';\nchar z = y;\nchar z2 = x[0];  // remember: in C/C++, arrays begin in 0\n</code></pre>\n<p>You can't declare twice the same variable:</p>\n<pre><code>char z = y;\nchar z = 'Play';  // 'Play' is not a char and you can't redeclare z\n</code></pre>\n<p>So, final code seems like;</p>\n<pre><code>#include \"stdafx.h\"\n#include &lt;iostream&gt;\nint main()\n{\n    using namespace std;\n\n    string x = \"Game\";\n    char y = x[0];\n\n    char z = y;\n    string z2 = \"Play\";\n\n    cout &lt;&lt; z &lt;&lt; endl;\n    cout &lt;&lt; x &lt;&lt; endl;\n}\n</code></pre>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-12-27T09:28:50.523", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-12-27T09:28:50.523", "ParentId": "20797979", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "855378"}, "20797979": {"ViewCount": "1653", "Body": "<pre><code>#include \"stdafx.h\"\n#include &lt;iostream&gt;\nint main()\n{\nusing namespace std;\nchar x = 'Game';\nchar y = x;\nchar z=y;\nchar z ='Play';\ncout &lt;&lt; z &lt;&lt; endl;\ncout &lt;&lt; x &lt;&lt; endl;\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>I am just a beginner of C++ program.I am using visual c++ 2012.I have this error while I am doing the programming....The error that visual c++ gave me is \"truncation from 'int' to 'char'\".Below is the following code.\nCan anyone tell me what should I do?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "20798125", "Title": "'initializing' : truncation from 'int' to 'char'", "CreationDate": "2013-12-27T09:20:18.380", "Id": "20797979", "CommentCount": "3", "FavoriteCount": "0", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2013-12-27T09:28:50.523", "Score": "0", "OwnerUserId": "3060281", "Tags": "<c++><visual-c++>", "AnswerCount": "3"}, "20798085": {"Id": "20798085", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>You would be better off just using <code>std::string</code></p>\n<pre><code>std::string x = \"Game\";\ncout &lt;&lt; x &lt;&lt; endl;\n</code></pre>\n<p>You must use <code>\"</code> instead of single quotes . Single quotes are used to represent a single <code>char</code> not an array</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2013-12-27T09:26:40.123", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-12-27T09:26:40.123", "ParentId": "20797979", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "1342730"}, "20798081": {"Id": "20798081", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>\u00a76.4.4.4.10</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_20797979_20798081_0\">The value of an integer character constant containing more than one\n  character (e.g., 'ab'), [...] is implementation-defined.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Chances are it's being treated as a <code>long</code> or similar type, which is \"truncated\" to fit into a <code>char</code>.</p>\n<p>You need double quotes and to use <code>std::string</code>:</p>\n<pre><code>string x = \"Game\";\n</code></pre>\n", "OwnerDisplayName": "user1508519", "LastActivityDate": "2013-12-27T09:26:30.043", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2013-12-27T09:26:30.043", "ParentId": "20797979", "CommentCount": "0"}});